Revisit the expected learning outcomes¶

By the end of this course students will be able to:

  1. Have a good understanding of the fundamental issues and challenges of machine learning
  2. Appropriately choose and appraise machine learning algorithms for predictive analytics in business
  3. Effectively use Python to process, summarize and visualize business data
  4. Effectively use Python to implement machine learning algorithms to solve business problems

Theory¶

What is machine learning?¶

A computer program is said to learn from experience $E$ with respect to some class of tasks $T$ and performance measure $P$, if its performance at tasks in $T$, as measured by $P$, improves with experience $E$. -- Tom Mitchell

Let's look at the fashion minst recognition example:

  • Task $T$: recognizing and classifying fashion products within images
  • Performance measure $P$: percent of fashion products correctly classified
  • Training experience $E$: a database of fashion products with given classifications
Machine learning is the study of computer algorithms that improve automatically through experience. It is seen as a subset of artificial intelligence. Machine learning algorithms build a mathematical model based on sample data, known as "training data", in order to make predictions or decisions without being explicitly programmed to do so. -- Wikipedia

Fig source: https://blog.digitalogy.co/

Different tasks/problems in supervised learning and unsupervised learning¶

Machine learning algorithms studied in this course¶

Linear regression

The average of the response is the linear combination of the weights and the input features. Note that the term linear here means the response variable linear in weights! Therefore, polynomial regression is regarded as the generalized linear model.

  • Models
    • Simple linear regression
    • Multiple linear regression
    • Polynomial regression
    • Lasso regression
    • Ridge regression
  • Tasks
    • Regression
  • Pros
    • Simple to understand
    • Good interpretability
  • Cons
    • Oversimplify or fail in non-linear problems or high dimensional data
    • Sensitive to outliers and noises

Logistic regression

  • Models
    • Two-class logistic regression
    • Multi-class logistic regression (one-vs-rest)
  • Tasks
    • Classification
  • Pros
    • Simple to understand
    • Good interpretability
    • Computational inexpensive
    • Perform well when data is linearly separable
  • Cons
    • Oversimplify or fail in non-linear problems or high dimensional data

Artificial neural networks

  • Models
    • Multi-layer perceptron (MLP)
  • Tasks
    • Regression
    • Classification
  • Pros
    • Perform well in non-linear problems
    • Perform well in high dimensional data
    • Perform well in large-scale data
  • Cons
    • Computationally expensive
    • Prone to overfit
    • Black-box model (poor interpretability)

Naive Bayes

  • Models
    • Gaussian naive Bayes
    • Categorical naive Bayes
    • Mixture naive Bayes
  • Tasks
    • Classification
  • Pros
    • Simple to understand
    • Good interpretability
    • Computational inexpensive
    • Perform relatively well with small data
  • Cons
    • Sensitive to the input features and label distributions
    • Poorly perform with high dimensional and large-scale data

K-nearest neighbors

  • Models
    • K-nearest neighbors
  • Tasks
    • Classification
  • Pros
    • Simple to understand
    • Insensitive to outliers
    • No assumptions about data
    • Perform relatively well with small data
  • Cons
    • Computational expensive
    • Perform well with numerical variables rather than nominal variables

Decision trees

  • Models
    • CART (gini impurity)
    • ID3 (information gain based on entropy)
    • C4.5 (information gain ratio based on entropy)
  • Tasks
    • Regression
    • Classification
  • Pros
    • Simple to understand
    • Insensitive to outliers
    • Good interpretability (white-box model)
    • No assumptions about data
    • Perform well with small data
    • Perform well with high dimensional data
    • Perform well in non-linear problems
  • Cons
    • Prone to overfitting

Tree-based ensemble learning

  • Models
    • AdaBoost
    • Random forest
    • Gradient boosted decision tree (GDBT)
  • Tasks
    • Regression
    • Classification
  • Pros
    • Simple to understand
    • Insensitive to outliers
    • No assumptions about data
    • Perform well with small data
    • Perform well with high dimensional data
    • Perform well in non-linear problems
  • Cons
    • GDBT is computational expensive
    • Instable outputs or training process
    • Prone to overfitting

Support vector machines

  • Models
    • Support vector machine with kernels
  • Tasks
    • Regression
    • Classification
  • Pros
    • Good to understand and theoretical guarantees regarding overfitting
    • Good interpretability
    • Computational inexpensive
    • Perform well with small data
    • Flexible selection of kernels for nonlinear problems
  • Cons
    • Sensitive to model parameters and kernel choice
    • Perform better in two-class classification problems than multi-class problems
There is no "best" algorithm for all scenarios and datasets. Generally speaking,
  • For small data which is linear separable, logistic regression and support-vector machines perform well. If you wish to estimate probabilities, logistic regression is the choice
  • For small data which is not linear separable, support-vector machines and decision trees perform well
  • For large-scale high dimensional data, neural networks and tree-based ensemble methods perform well. Random forest can be implemented in parallel, therefore, its training can be faster than neural networks. However, neural networks, particularly deep neural networks has a high potential in performance for larger data and can provide end-to-end solution.

Cost/loss function¶

  • Mean squared errors for regression
  • Cross entropy for classification
  • Data loss + structural loss (e.g., ridge regression, lasso regression, SVM soft margin classifier)

Model evaluation¶

  • Regression

    • Mean squared errors
    • Mean absolute error
    • R squared

  • Classification

    • Accuracy
    • Precision (e.g., recommender systems, information retrieval)
    • Recall (e.g., fraud detection)
    • F1 measure
    • AUC/ROC (for two-class classification)
